<font color="#FF0000">TO BOB NARVAEZ</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 27  5:36:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Bob Narvaez:<br><br>
You said:<br><br>
&gt;&quot;It is amazing that Viet Nam has become what we wanted it to be, a powerful democratic country.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
Nothing could be farther away from the truth!<br><br>
Vietnam, today, is a country which imposes a &quot;state run Buddhist religion&quot; and continues to engage in supression of free speech in the interest of &quot;state secrets&quot;. Is this a &quot;democracy&quot;? I think not.<br><br>
It seems that the lineage of leaders of the peoples republic of Vietnam have historically duped everyone, beginning with my &quot;favorite&quot; person, Jane Fonda. Her involvement with North Vietnam was classic proletarian propaganda of the highest order, and was in my view, treason.<br><br>
It is even more interesting, that after the fall of Saigon and the imposition of the &quot;peoples republic&quot; over the entire country, these people even devoured their own kind in the fear that even the Viet Cong would become a political threat to those in power. <br><br>
The present rush of companies to do business in Vietnam and the support of our civilian government to that end by the opening of diplomatic relations is an act I find repugnant. History has shown that attempting to use this tactic to change the course of any country is nothing more than snively bribery that never, in the end, really works. Furthermore, as a Vietnam Veteran, I cannot help but feel that this is a dishonor to those who lost their lives in the Vietnam War, and an invalidation of the blood, sweat, and tears of those who survived.<br><br>
I invite you to examine the web site of the &quot;Free Vietnam Alliance&quot; at:<br><br>
http://www.fva.org/<br><br>
...to learn more of what the contemporary govenment of Vietnam is doing in the eyes of displaced and exiled Vietnam Nationals.<br><br>
What I see in our present love-in with the government of Vietnam is a pathetic shadow of Neville Chamberlin waving a promise signed by Adolph Hitler to be a good little boy.<br><br>
Fortunes were made in the Vietnam War on the backs of those whose names appear on The Wall because of the incompetant politics and bizarre military strategy of our government. It seems that some are again driven by money in the continuation of this saga. I can see no other reason at the core for our diplomatic relations than pressure by business to open the floodgates once again. This time, upon whose backs will the profits be made? How many Buddhist monks will have to burn themselves alive again, as they did back in the 1950's? There is really something that has been going wrong in that country for many, many, many years.<br><br>
During the Vietnam War, the GI slang for the enemy was &quot;gooks&quot;. Those who run Vietnam today are no better. In my view, they are still gooks. 
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


